{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608762/1958051001/0805.xml":{"full_text":"Today\u2014Special Section on New Zoning Regulations for Washington\nWEATHER FORECAST\nConsiderable cloudiness tonight, low S 3.\nCloudy, mild with a chance of showera\nSunday (Pull report. Page A-2.)\nTemperature* Today\nMidnight dl g a m... A3 11 a.m. ..(Ml\n4 am. 54 g a.m. 53 Noon 8.7\n3a m. ...6? 10 a.m 57 1 p.m....6A\n106th Year. No. 130. Phone ST. 3-5000 B WASHINGTON, D. C. t SATURDAY, MAY 10, 1958-44 PAGES Hem. Delivered: UU 5 CENTS\njUt\ne\nSAFETY GUARDS ON THE MARCH\u2014Young\nsters from St. Gabriel\u2019s School in Washington\nmarch briskly past the stands in today\u2019s School\nSafety Patrol Parade along Constitution avenue.\nArmed Forces\nShow Opens\n100,000 View\nAndrews Display\nBy JERRY O LEARY, Jr.\nStar 6tuff Writer\nAn estimated 100.000 persons\nvisited Andrews Air Force Base\ntoday to see the biggest dem\nonstration of the Nation's\nmilitary power ever staged.\nThe Armed Forces Day\nshow, presented with near-per\nfect 70-degree weather and\nsunny skies, is expected to\ndraw a quarter of a million\npeople today and tomorrow.\nSunday is expected to be part\nly cloudy with a chance of\nshowers.\nDefense Secretary McElroy\nand Gen. Nathan F. Twining,\nchairman of the Joint Chiefs\nof Staff, headed the list of\nnational leaders, military men\nand members of the diplo\nmatic corps who turned out\nfor the big show.\nForty-six special events,\ncapped by an air show fea\nturing the hottest military\nplanes in the Nation\u2019s arsenal,\nwere among the thousand ex\nhibits opened free to the pub\nlic today by the Air Force.\nArmy. Navy, Marines and\nCoast Guard. The two-hour\nair show, starting today and\ntomorrow at 2 p.m., features\nthe precision team-flying of\nthe Air Force Thunderbirds\nand the Navy's Blue Angels.\nThe world's fastest and only\nsupersonic bomber, the B-58\nHustler, and six Century series\nfighter planes also will go\nthrough their aerial paces\nover the exhibit area.\nA mass jump of airborne\ntroops will end the program at\nft p.m. today and tomorrow.\nAnother parachute show will\nContinued on Page A-14, Col. 2\nPflimlin Will Try\nTo Form Cabinet\nPARIS. May 10 UP).\u2014 Pierre\nPflimlin will accept President\nRene Coty's request to try to\nform the 25th postwar gov\nernment, reliable sources said\ntoday. He will go before the\nFrench Parliament for ap\nproval Tuesday.\nMr. Pflimlin is expected to\ngive his formal response to the\nPresident tonight or tomorrow.\nHis own Catholic Popular Re\npublican Movement decided\n45-2 today to back him fully.\nMr. Pflimlin sought National\nAssembly support for an Al\ngerian policy roughly the same\nas the government which fell\n25 days ago over Algeria.\nFOR YOUR\nDREAM HOUSE\nSHOP\nTHE STAR\nREAL ESTATE\nSECTION\nTODAY\nToday and every Saturday\nshop The Star for a wide\nvariety ot best real estate\nofferings by leading build\ners and brokers throughout\nthe Washington area.\nFor the home of your\ndreams, in the right loca\ntion, at a price you can\nafford to pay.\nSHOP THE STAR FIRST\nBEFORE YOU BUY\n\n31,000 Pupils Parade\nIn Salute to Safety\n20 States Represented in Column;\nSchool Slogans Stress Space Theme\nA gigantic salute to safety swept down Constitution ave\nnue today before an estimated 120,000 persons.\nMore than 31,000 boys and girls from 20 States\u2014including\n7,000 from the Washington area\u2014proudly strutted between\nNinth and Seventeenth streets in a five-hour tribute to the\nyoungsters in white Sam Browne belts who look after the\nsafety of their schoolmates.\nThe largest annual Washing\nton parade, the march was\npart of the 22nd safety patrol\nassembly sponsored by the\nAmerican Automobile Associa\ntion. 4\nPrecision marching units,\nbands, majoi*ttes. and Sputnik\ninspired slogans and floats\nabounded.\n\"Sputniks in Space\"\n\"Sputnik* Speed Around in\nSpace; Children Need a Safer\nPlace\" waa the John F. Cook\nSchool\u2019s slogan. St. Gabriel's\nSchool urged: \"Lt\u2019s Put Acci\ndents Into Outer Space.\u201d\nThe Shaw Junior School's\nbanner warned: \"You\u2019ll Be.the\nFirst to Mars if You Walk Be- i\nI tween Parked Cars.\u201d\nThe marchers started at 9\na.m. They could hardly have\nasked for better weather. The\ntemperature hovered in the low\n70s as a slight breeze counter\nacted the bright sun.\nMembers of Congress and i\nofficials of police, governmental\nand safety organizations packed\nthe reviewing stand opposite\nthe Washington Monument.\n5.780 From Georgia\nThe largest out-of-town dele\ngation participating in the pa\nrade was from Georgia, repre\nsented by 5,780 youngster*\nsmartly dressed in white and\nlight blue uniforms.\nAfter the paraders finished\nI their marching, they dispersed\nfor sight-seeing. Some 4,000\nplanned to go to Andrews Air\nForce Base for the special\nArmed Forces Day show there.\nA group from Key West, Fla.,\nreceived a trophy this morning\nfor having traveled the greatest\ndistance to enter the parade.\nOne group of 500 from De\nkalb. Ga., were the only known\ncasualty The youngsters never\njmade it to Washington. Their\ntram developed trouble in\n.Greenboro. N. C. Dekalb was\nwell-represen4ed, however, by\n700 other youngsters.\nLater today, the AAA will\naward 37 prizes to individual\nunits in the march. One of tne\nhighlights will be presentation\nJet Airliners Noisiest\nWhile Being Taxied\nBy the Associated Press\nThe big noise of jet trans\nports may come from taxiing\u2014\nnot takeoffs.\nThus, a major problem looms\nfor airports which will be used\nby the giant passenger jets\nwhen they come into com\nmercial operation.\nThis was reported today to\nthe Acoustical Society of\nAmerica by physicists Laymon\nN. Miller and Robert M. Hoover\not Bolt Beranek Newman.\nInc., Cambridge, Mass. The\ngroup is meeting at the Wil\nlard Hotel.\nTheir findings were based on\nsound measurements during\noperations of two European jet\ntransports, the twin-engine\nFrench Caravelle and the four\nengine British Comet. There\nare no American jet transports\nnow in operation. But the two\nphysicists noted that the\nFrench and British jets are\nsmaller and have engines of\nlower thrust than American\ntransports that will soon go in\noperation.\nMr. Miller and Mr. Hoover\nfound in their tests that the\nyise from the transports was\n\u00a9he Itiettiim Sfatf\ny J y WITH SUNDAY MORNING EDITION \\S\nMore than 31,000 children marched in the big\nErocession, featuring 80 floats, 70 marching\nands and dozens of drum majorettes.\u2014Star\nStaff Photo.\nof the Clark Griffith Memorial\nTrophy to the local school\nwhose float best illustrates\n\"sportsmanship in safety.\u201d\nLeading off the parade was\nthe Army Band, under the di\nrection of Major Hugh Curry.\nYesterday a 10-year-old Hy\nattsville, Md., boy, Larry Fox,\nfrom the Langley Park Ele\nmentary School, received a cita\ntion from Gen. Nathan F.\nTwining, chairman of the Joint\nChiefs of Staff, for saving the\nlife of a girl.\nOthers who received lile-i\nsaving awards from the gen- 1\neral were Effie Passas, 12. Lan\ncaster, Pa.; Sue Marie Gil\nchrist, 13, Toledo, Ohio; George!\nRaymond Czech. 14. Little Falls,\nMinn.; Bobby Jones, 18. Arena,\nWis.: Clarene Linz, jr., 11.\nNorth Little Rock. Ark., and\nTerry Rivelli. 13. William Smith\nSchool, Aurora, Colo.\nIn last night's drill competi-,\ntion at Fort Myer 25 teams\nj from seven States and the!\nDistrict of Columbia competed.\nWinners were:\nElementary division (girls): 1\u2014\nPottstown Elementary Sehool, Potts\ntown. Pa \u2019.'\u2014North End School.\nOreenbelt. Md :t\u2014St Gabriels\nSchool. Washington\nElementary division (boy*); 1\u2014\nPalnsvill* Cavaliers. Painsville. Ohio;\nJacksonville City Schools. Jack- 1\nsonvtlle Beach Bchool Safety Patrol, I\nJacksonville Fla.\nJunior division (girl*): I\u2014St\nGabr el's School, Washington; 2 \u2014The\nOaklawn Band. Oaklawn. N. J.\nJunior division (boys); l\u2014Potts\ntown Junior High Sehool. 2\u2014St\nGabriel's School. .\u2019l\u2014J ackson ville\nSafety Patrol.\nSenior division (girls)- I\u2014Bover\nton Area High School Color Guard.\nBryertown. Pa 2\u2014Pottstown Benior\nHigh School Olrls Color Guard: 3\u2014\u2022\nPottstown Senior High School Girls\nDrill Team\nSenior division (bovs>: I\u2014potts\ntown Benlor High School Boys Drill\nTeam\nFBI Chief Marks\n34th Year in Job\nBy the Associated Press\nJ. Edgar Hoover today marks\ni the 34th anniversary of his\nappointment as director of the\nFBI.\nMr. Hoover has served con\ntinuously in that post under\nfive Presidents, starting with\nCalvin Coolldge. and under 12\n'Attorneys General.\nloudet when they were being\ntaxied than when they were\ntaking off.\nFor takeoffs, they reported,\nthe noise at a distance of 1.000\nfeet ranged from 100 decibles\nin the lowest frequency band\nto about 80 decibels in the\nhigher bands. This was slightly\nless than the taxiing noise at\n100 feet in the low frequency\nbands and less by a greater\nmargin in the higher bands.\nAt a distance of 4.000 feet,\nthe scientists said, the takeoff\nnoise was generally less than\neither the idle engine or taxi\nnoise at 100 feet.\n\"The data from these two\naircraft show that taxi opera\ntions at 100 feet will generally\nproduce the highest noise lev\nels outside terminal buildings\nif the terminal facilities are lo\ncated more than about 1.000\nfeet away from the runways,\nthe scientists said.\n\"If the jet airliners are not\nallowed to taxi closer than\nabout 400 feet to the terminal\nbuildings then the takeoff noise\nlevels at 1.000 feet would be\nmore comparable to the taxi\nr4*e.\"\nGirl Charges\nRape Attempt\nCabin John Man\nHeld for Assault\nA 25-year-old Cabin John\ni (Md.) man was charged with\nattempted rape today after a\nfrightened 17-year-old girl said\nshe was abducted at gunpoint\nfrom a parked car and forced\nto accompany the man.\nThe suspect was jailed on\ntwo counts of assault and bat\ntery and one charge of assault\niwith intent to rape. He was\nidentified by Montgomery\nCounty police as Chester M.\nMills of the 7800 block of Tom\nlinson avenue, a flooring con\ntractor.\nMills was in police custody\nabout seven hours after the\nvictim, bruised and cut, came\nto the Bethesda police substa\ntion and reported that a\nbearded man who claimed to\n,be ft State trooper, had forced\n(her to accompany him.\nCounty Police Pvts. Jesse M.\nJennings and Demetrius G.\nKaponin investigated the story\ntold by the pretty teen-ager\nand her 19-year-old boy friend.\nParked Early Today\nThe young couple told police i\nI they were parked early today j\noff Bells Mill road, west of Old\nGeorgetown road, when an un\nkempt man, waving a flashlight\nand an automatic pistol, ap\nproached and said he was a\nState trooper. Claiming they\nwere illegally parked, the man\nordered the girl into his car\nand told her escort to lead the i\nway to a police station, the\nj couple reported.\nThen, the girl said, the i\napspect drove off swiftly in the!\nopposite direction. She said he!\nmade indecent proposals m the\ncar. She managed to open the j\ncar door and hurl herself to\nthe roadway as the auto\ngathered speed, the girl said.\nShe was treated for cuts and\nbruises at Suburban Hospital.\nPolice said the girl\u2019s boy\nfriend followed the fleeing car,\ni.spotted its tag number and\nrescued the girl when she\nleaped out.\nMills, who is married and\nhas two children, was picked\nup by police as he was driving\nto work. With him were his\nwife and one of their children.\nThe suspect\u2019s gun, police said,\nturned out to be an air pistol\nwhich was a replica of a 45-\ncaliber automatic.\nJailed in Rockville under\n$6,000 bond. Mills is scheduled\nto appear in Bethesda People\u2019s\nCourt Tuesday for a preliminary\nhearing.\ni\nSouth Africa Accepts\nPresident's Invitation\nPRETORIA, South Africa.\nMay 10 UP).\u2014' The South African\ngovernment today accepted the\ninvitation of President Eisen\nhower to a conference of the\n12 nations directly interested\nto insure that Antarctica be\nused only for peaceful purposes.\nThe President\u2019s lnvitaion\nwas extended a week ago. It\nalso envisages drawing up a\ntreaty providing for freedom\nfor scientific investigation in\nAntarctica.\nSTOCKS\nIN THE SPOTLIGHT\nNEW YORK /P> \u2014Following are the\nsites <add ihii, high. low. dosing price\nand net change of the 20 most active\nstocks for the week:\nSales High. Low. Close Chg.\nAm Mot 1750 13* 11* 13* +2*\nOlinMa lOu.'i 35V. 33* 347.\nLorillard 1800 sMl* 54\u2019. 58 +3*\nLoews 1705 17* 15* 17*+2*\nRexal! Dr 148; 18* 14* 15*+ 1*\nBaobitt 1301 7* s\u2019. 7**l*\nBethStl 133*.\u2019 40* 30* 40*+ 1*\nHaveg Ind 1310 30* 27* 29*+ 2*\nGen Met 127 0 30* 37* 30*+]*\nA m .tad la 1233 12* 11 11\ni Getty Oil 1212 27* 25* 27* +l*\nSperry Rd 1181 10* 17V* 18*+1*\nj Snell Tr 1107 21* 21 21*+\nRoy Dutc 1084 48* 45* 45*\u2014\njU 8 Steel 1073 82* 81*\nl3td ONJ 1034 55* 54* 54*\u2014\nICaieCo 1030 18* 17* 18*+\njFairch Eng 058 IC* 10* 12*+ 1*\ntaring Air 035 42* 30* 30%\u2014CVa\nIf*', Ch 927 24% 22* 23*\u20141\nRevised Zoning Code\nStarts Here Monday\nEmployment,\nHome Building\nAnd Sales Rise\nDrop in Number\nOs Insured Jobless\nBiggest, in Months\nBy the Associated Press\nNew Government report* re\nflect improvement last month\nin employment, home building\nand retail sales.\nVarious Federal agencies\nannounced yesterday that:\n1. Farm employment ln-\nI creased more than usual In late\nApril to come within 1 per\n'cent of the number employed\nthe same time last year.\n2. Unemployment among\nworkers covered by jobless in\nsurance dropped by 66,900 dur\ning the week ended April 26\nthe largest decline for any week\nsince last July. Forty one\nStates reported reductions.\nHowever, that week\u2019s total of\n3,265.700 in insured unemploy\nment was more than double\nthat of the corresponding period\nlast year.\n3. Housing activity picked up\nin several fields, slightly ex\nceeding April, 1957, in the\nnumber of new units put under\nconstruction.\n4. Retail sales increased 2 per\ncent during the month, with\nthe biggest improvement in\ndurable goods.\nDoubt Upturn Before Fall\nAt Hot Springs, Va., Secre\ntary of Commerce Week* said!\nthe great majority of his Busi- j\nness Advisory Council seem to\nfeel the recession has gone\nabout as deep as it will go.\nBut he added that these corpo\nration executives doubt there\nwill be a recovery before fall.\n\"A speck more optimism\u201d over\nthe business outlook since the\ngroup met last in March was\nreported by Roger M. Blough,\nboard chairman of United\nStates Steel Corp. and head of\njthe council's Economic Policy!\nCommittee.\nA special seven-member anti\nrecession committee of the BAC,\nnamed in April at Mr. Weeks\u2019\nrequest to recommend a pre\nscription for recovery, came up\nyesterday with a report pro-i\nposing:\n1. That President Eisenhower\ncall on industry and labor tor\na voluntary one-year morato- j\nnum on both wage boosts and\nprice increases, g\n2. That no tax reduction be\nasked now, but that \"if the de-!\ndine in general consumption\ncontinues.\" a flat percentage\njcut be made in all personal m\njeome tax rates.\nDebate Reveals Tax Split\nThe moratorium idea pro\nvoked no discussion. But the tax\nrecommendation touched off\ndebate that revealed a split.\nSome members called for a\nquick 10 per cent, $7 billion tax\nicut. Others protested that tax\nreduction was unnecessary;\nthat it would be inflationary\nSee ECONOMIC, Page A-3\nLANHAM FIRE\nKILLS 3,000\nPARAKEETS\nThree thousand para\nkeets burned to death last\nnight in a fire which de\nstroyed the breeding build\ning of L. A. Goodwin, jr.,\nin Lanham, Md. It was the\nsecond fire in the building\nsince January of last year.\nMr. Goodwin estimated\nthe loss at $12,000 to stock\nand equipment and $3,000\nto the two-story cinder\nblock building at the rear\nof his home. 9333 Fourth\nstreet. He said the loss\nis partially covered by in\nsurance.\nPrince Georges County\nFire Marshal Lawrence\nWoltz said inspectors have\nnot been able to determine\nthe cause of last night\u2019s\nfire or the previous one,\nwhich also destroyed most\nof Mr. Goodwin's breeding\nstock.\nMr. Goodwin, a builder\nwho supplies area pet\nstores with the birds as a\nbusiness sideline, said he\nstill has 300 birds housed\nin nis garage.\n\"But,\u201d he said, \u201cit\ntakes about a year to re\ncuperate from a loss like\nthis. Guess I'll just quit\nnow.\"\nRed China Suspends\nAll Trade With Japan\nImport and Export Licenses Stopped;\nTrading Firms Contracts Nullified\nTOKYO, May 10 (ff).\u2014 Communist China notified Japan\ntoday It Is suspending all business between the two nations\n\"because of Prime Minister Nobusuke Kishl's hostile attitude\ntoward China.\u201d\nThe head of Red China's trade delegation, which has\nbeen negotiating In Tokyo since March 30, Issued a statement\nsaying his government has'\nstopped Issuing Import and\nexport licenses to Japan. Ma\njor Japanese trading Arms also\nwere informed by cable from\nShanghai that their contracts\nhad been nullified.\nThe action followed Chinese\nForeign Minister Chen Yl\u2019s\nblistering attack on Premier\nKishi yesterday. The Japanese\ngovernment termed the Com\nmunist move intervention in\nJapanese Internal affairs. It\nwas considered aimed at dis\ncrediting Mr. Kishi\u2019s conserva\ntive government in the May 22\ngeneral elections.\nChina last month nullified a\n$l9O million trade agreement\nwith Japan when Japan re\nfused to giant the Communist\nflag diplomatic recognition in\nTokyo.\nLi Chuo-chin. head of the\nChinese delegation in Tokyo,\ntoday told Japan his delegation i\nwas discontinuing more than 40\ndays of negotiations \u201cbecause\nKhrushchev Bars List\nOs Dulles' Set Topics\nMOSCOW, May 10 UP).\u2014Pre\nmier Khrushchev says he still\nwants to sit down with other\nheads of government but he\nisn\u2019t about to accept Secretary\nof State Dulles\u2019 list of what\nshould be discussed at the sum\nmit.\nDeclaring the Soviets have\n\"nerves as tough as Alpine\nRussia Seen Making No Deals on\nAdvisers. Pog* A-3\nrope.\u201d Khrushchev told diplo\nmats and officials at the Cze\nchoslovak Embassy\u2019s National\nDay reception last night it\nwould take more than world\ntensions to frighten the Rus\nsians.\nWestern correspondents were\nnot invited to the reception, but\nother newsmen present gave\nthis account:\n\u201cWe want summit talks.\u201d the\nPremier said. \"We want them\nin the same degree the Western\u2014\n1\nLincoln Papers\nLost in Blaze\nGALESBURG, 111., May 10\nj (\u00a3*).\u2014A wealth of Illinois his\ntorical documents, some papers\nsigned by Abraham Lincoln\namong them, was lost last night\nin a fire that destroyed the\nGalesburg Public Library.\nLoss of the 57-year-old build\ning and the 122.000 volumes it\nhoused was estimated at $1\nmillion.\n1 Failure of two of the city's\nfive water wells hampered ef\nforts to quell the blaze. Fire\nmen were able to play only a\nsingle hose on flames licking\nupward to the second floor\nwhere the Lincoln papers and\nother historical items were\nstored in a vault.\n\u201cFrom what 1 can see, the\nvault is gone.\u201d City Manager\nRaymond Harbaugh said after\nviewing the smoldering runis.\nBRICKED-UP DOOR\nEvangelist Trapped\nBy Italian Landlady\nFONDI, Italy, May 10 (i P).\u2014\nA Catholic landlady got tired\nof Protestants trooping in to a\ntwo-room church set up in her\nhouse by an Evangelist min\nister.\nSo, with court permission,\nshe had him isolated from his\ncongregation behind a bricked\nup door.\nMrs. Gemma Rasile first\nwarned the Rev. Umberto\nRighettl he must get out or be\nimprisoned in his church by\nthe blocking of the only entry.\nHe refused to budge.\nThe bricklayers came Tues\nday.\nFrhis second-floor win-\nof Kishl's hostile attitude and\nobstruction.\"\nLi's delegation has been\nnegotiating for implementation\nof the Japan-Red China steel\nagreement amounting to 200\nmillion pounds ($560 million)\nover a five-year period, signed\nlast February in Peiping. A\ncontract for 150.000 tons of\nJapanese steel and iron had\nbeen initialled.\nIn his press statement Li\nsaid \u201cthe Japanese government\nimposed improper conditions\nfor China\u2019s shipment of rice (in\npayment for the steel) and de\nlayed our negotiations.\u201d\nMeanwhile, major Japanese\ntrading companies received\ncabled messages from Chinese\ntrading concerns in Shanghai\ncancelling all outstanding con\ntracts. The messages specifi\ncally saidAhe cancellation ap\nplies also to Chinese shipments\nto balance Red China's trade\ndebts to Japan. Such debts\ntotaled B'j million pounds\n($23.8 million) as of March 31.\npowers should want them. But\nif they want to maintain a\ntense situation, then it must be\nthat way. We can live in ten\nsion, too.\"\nCommenting on summit topics\nproposed by Secretary Dulles\nand indorsed this week by At\nlantic Alliance foreign minis\nters. Khrushchev asserted \u201cnone\nof them is acceptable.\u201d\n\u201cHe wants the German Dem\nocratic Republic (East Ger\nmany to be liquidated.\u201d\nKhrushchev commented. \u201cIt is\nimpossible, it\u2019s madness. We\ndon\u2019t want our heads on the\nchopping block.\u201d\nAt the windup of their three\nday meeting in Copenhagen\nWednesday, the 15 NATO for\neign ministers suggested that\nthe summit parley deal with\nreunification of Germany and\nother key East-West issues.\nMoscow contends that German\nreunification should be dis\ncussed directly between the\nsatellite regime and the West\nGerman government in order\nto protect the Communist gov\nernment from being submerged\nin all-German free elections\nunder the Big Four.\nTripoli Rioters\nBurn U.S. Library\nBEIRUT, Lebanon. May 10\n(\u00a3*).\u2014Rioters burned the United\nStates Information Service\nlibrary today in the North\nLebanon seaport of Tripoli.\nReports from the scene said\ngovernment forces had brought\nithe rioting\u2014serious for a time\n\u2014under control.\nRifle fire broke out in the\ncenter of the city earlier today.\nReports by telephone said a\ncurfew now has been clamped\non one district.\nThese reports said rioters\nsmashed their way into the\nclosed USIS library, hauled out\nbooks, then set the place on\nfire. The amount of damage\ncaused could not Immediately\nbe determined.\ndow the -etranded clergyman\n1 called out to his followers: \u201cThe\ncaptain does not abandon the\nr ship and I will not abandon\nmy church.\nFor three days he used a 20-\nfoot rope and bucket to pull up\ns groceries they brought.\nYesterday Mrs. Rasile, moved\nby pity, said she couldn't stand\nt it any longer, and had the\n3 bricklayers reopen the door,\ne The minister came out. hag\ni gard but triumphant, and shook\nhands with his followers.\nSignora Rasile said her at\ntorney told her it would have\ntaken him six months to get a\norder to reopen the door.\nREAL ESTATE\nSECTION\nPages C*l to C-14\nTight Curbs\nContained in\nCompromise\nWashington s long awaited\ntoning revision, which imposes\nbrand-new restrictions on the\nuse of almost all the private\nland in the city, was made pub\nlic today by the District Zon\ning Commission.\nThe new zoning code goes\ninto effect at 12:01 a.m. Mon-\nSt* special section an new code, in\ncluding test of regulations, mops\nand analysis. Section I.\nday. Any applications for new\nbuilding permits filed after that\nmoment must comply with the\nnew zoning rules.\nIn its Anal form, the cod*\nrepresents a clear-cut compro\nmise between the extreme pro\nposals of factions which, for the\nHast three years, have waged\none of the bitterest civic fights\nin District history.\nThe code, for example, sub\nstantially tightens previous con\ntrols on the kinds and sizes of\nnew buildings which will be per\nmitted throughout the city.\nRigid Plan Toned Down\nAt the same time, it tone*\ndown sharply some of the rigid\nrestrictions proposed by Harold\nM. Lewis, the New York zoning\nexpert hired by the city in 1954\nj to rewrite the 38-year-old zon\ning code.\nIn general, however, th*\nZoning Commission has fol\nlowed the outline proposed by\nMr. Lewis for the new code,\nand has utilized many of the\nnew types of zoning technique*\nhe suggested.\nLt. Col. Thomas B. Hunter,\nassistant District Engineer\nCommissioner, called the new\ncode \"a fair program\u201d for the\ncity and \"a modest one in its\ndegree of restrictions com\npared with the provisions of\na number of new zoning codes\n|in other cities.\"\nHe said the commission and\nstaff members who have\nworked on the new code rec\nognize that it is not perfect and\nthat a number of modification*\nmay have to be made as time\ngoes an\nBut he said he felt that the\nover-all effect would be to sta\nbilize values in the city and to\nbring zoning into much closer\nrelationship to the way land\nactually is being used than did\nthe old code.\nOne of the major new pro\nvisions is a requirement that\noff-street parking spaces be\nprovided to serve all new com\nmercial buildings except those\n'in the downtown business area.\nThe elimination of such re\nquirements downtown, however,\nis a major victory for business\ngroups,\nRule Now in Effect\nAs adopted, the new rules are\neffective immediately. Appli\ncations for building permit*\nfiled up to the close of busi\nness yesterday, however, are\nto be processed under the old\nrules if they do not require\nmajor modifications.\nDespite efforts to keep the\neffective date of the new code\nsecret, officials said they were\nflooded yesterday with more\nthan 100 applications for build\ning permits by builders who\nwanted their applications proc\nessed under the old rules. In\nview o t the rush officials de\ncided to keep the District\nBuilding permit office open an\nhour beyond its usual 3:30 p.m.\nclosing time to accommodate\nthe latecomers.\nOfficial copies of the new\ncode will be available for $1.50\neach Monday morning at Room\n1108, District Building.\nFAITH FOUND\nAT LOURDES\nTIRED AT HOME, o 78 year-old\nFrenchman Finds himjelf carefree\nand young again during hit yearly\nservice to the sick at the world\nfamous shrine at Lourdes. Today's\nillustration of The Power of Foith\nis on Page A-9.\nPARISHIONERS of the Immonuel\nChurch-on-the-Hill in Alexandria\nwill weor their best gardening\nclothes to church tomorrow, with the\nmission of planting trees to beautify\nthe grounds. The story is on Page\nA 6.\nGuide for Readers\nAmuse'ts C-12-13 Music C D\nChurches A-6-9 Obituary B-B\nClassified D-l-8 Real Estate C-1 -14\nComics A-12-13 Society D-R\nCrossword A 12 Sports A-10-11\nEditorial A 4 TV Radio A-U\nEdit'l Articles A S Zoning\nLost, Found A-3 Section .8-1-7\nHave The Star Delivered to\nYour Home Daily and Sunday\nDial STerling 3-5000","height":"28800","width":"18089"}}
